\description{
\code{indicator()} attaches one or more technical indicators to an existing
\code{\link[=chart]{chart()}}, or renders an indicator as a standalone chart. Each indicator
is displayed in its own subchart panel below the main price chart.

If \code{\link[=chart]{chart()}} has not been called beforehand, \code{indicator()} creates a
standalone indicator chart — in this case, \code{data} must be provided
explicitly.

See \code{vignette(topic = "charting", package = "talib")} for a comprehensive
guide.
}
\details{
\code{indicator()} operates in two modes depending on how \code{FUN} is passed:
\subsection{Single Indicator Mode}{

Pass a bare function name (without parentheses) and its arguments via
\code{...}:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{chart(BTC)
indicator(RSI, n = 14)
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Multi-Indicator Mode}{

Pass one or more indicator calls (with parentheses) to merge them onto
a single subchart panel:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{chart(BTC)
indicator(RSI(n = 10), RSI(n = 14), RSI(n = 21))
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

Each indicator retains its own arguments. Different indicator types can
be freely combined on the same panel:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{indicator(RSI(n = 14), MACD())
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

Multi-indicator mode requires an existing \code{\link[=chart]{chart()}} — it cannot be used
standalone.
}

\subsection{Standalone Mode}{

When no \code{\link[=chart]{chart()}} has been called, a standalone indicator chart is created.
The \code{data} argument is required in this case:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{indicator(RSI, data = BTC, n = 14)
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

The chart title is automatically derived from the indicator function name,
converting \code{snake_case} to Title Case.
}

\subsection{Panel Layout}{

When subcharts are present, the main price panel occupies 70\% of the total
height by default (configurable via \code{options(talib.chart.main = ...)}), and
the remaining space is divided equally among subchart panels.
}
}
